  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA179-kiḷavi">itu maṉaimaruṭci.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is the refusal of the house.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA179">
<l>            illeḻu vayalai yīṟṟā tiṉṟeṉap</l>
<l>            pantunilat teṟintu pāvai nīkki</l>
<l>            yavvayi ṟalaittaveṉ ceyviṉaik kuṟumakaṇ</l>
<l>            māṉamarp paṉṉa maiya ṉōkkamo</l>
<l>            ṭiyāṉun tāyu maṭuppat tēṉoṭu </l>
<l>            tīmpā luṇṇāḷ vīṅkuvaṉaḷ vimmi</l>
<l>            nerunalu maṉaiyaṇ maṉṉē yiṉṟē</l>
<l>            maiyaṇaṟ kāḷai poypuka lāka</l>
<l>            maruñcura miṟantaṉa ḷeṉpataṉ</l>
<l>            muruntēr veṇpaṉ mukiḻnakai tiṟantē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">Because the newly calved cow had eaten the Vayalai rising by the house,</l>
<l>my apt(?) little daughter,</l>
<l rend="indent2">who threw [her] ball to the ground,</l>
<l rend="indent2">rejected [her] doll [and] slapped that belly,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">avvayiṟu alaitta</term>: this might refer to the cow's belly, or, as T.V.G. explains, to the pretty belly of the girl, as a gesture of woe (with a different sandhi split, namely am <term xml:lang="ta">vayiṟu</term>). (For a parallel where women in play seem to be slapping their bellies see NA 398.4.)</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">did not eat the sweet milk with honey,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while [her] mother and I were feeding [her],</l>
<l rend="indent2">with a mad look as if being at strife with the animal(?)<note place="foot">T.V.G. takes this to be a description of the enchanting eyes of the girl and takes <term xml:lang="ta">amarppu</term> as another word of comparison. <term xml:lang="ta">maiyal</term>, however, seems to have predominantly negative connotations (cf. NA 146.10, 181.9; KT 374.7).</note>.</l>
<l>As one swelling, sobbing,</l>
<l>even yesterday indeed she was like that.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Today,</l>
<l rend="indent">with a bosom that rejoices in the lies of the black-bearded young man,</l>
<l>she has gone to traverse the difficult desert, they say,</l>
<l rend="indent2">her teeth, white as quills, opened in a budding smile.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
